options.tex:
%text
If angle between the normal to the plane and the $y$ axis is $\theta$,
%
\begin{align}
\cos\theta=-\dfrac{4}{3\sqrt{10}}
\end{align}

%text
If angle between the normal to the plane and the $y$ axis is $\theta$,
%
\begin{align}
\cos\theta=\dfrac{3}{4}
\end{align}

reason.tex:
%text
Using the scalar dot product of two vectors,
%
\begin{align}
  (\vector{5}{-4}{7})\cdot\hat j&=|\vector{5}{-4}{7}|\cos\theta \\
    \therefore -4&=3\sqrt{10}\cos\theta\\
  \therefore \cos\theta&=-\dfrac{4}{3\sqrt{10}}
\end{align}

options.tex:
%text
Angle between the $y$ axis and the normal to the plane is $\theta$, therefore angle $\phi$ between the $y$ axis and the surface is
%
\begin{align}
  \phi&=\pi/2-\theta=\sin^{-1}\left(\dfrac{4}{3\sqrt{10}}\right)
\end{align}
